storyText: Alvira and Senna walked into the restaurant hand in sweaty hand with quite different expectations: Senna was going to propose tonight, and Alvira had no idea.
He took a deep breath, trying to calm his nerves as worst case scenarios ran through his mind.
The entrance of the restaurant was dazzling; chandeliers spread their warm light onto the delicate place settings of all the tables filled with guests dressed to the nines.
Through the floor-to-ceiling arched windows of the back wall, they saw the sun setting onto the Pacific ocean.
This was surely one of the best restaurants on the west coast, situated right on the beach.
Senna gave his name to the host, who quickly located their reservation with an almost comically wide customer-service smile.
He led them to a table right by the window.
He brought out some very small menus, with a short list of the celebrity chef's carefully selected daily dishes written in a loopy, cursive font unadorned by any mention of prices.
Senna slipped off to the bathroom to check to make sure the ring was in order.
The ring contained a canary diamond that had been in his grandmother’s wedding ring, and it was a brilliant stone that was accentuated by the small white diamonds encircling it.
He walked back to the table after handing the small, velvet box to a waiter at the front podium.
He came back just as their waiter was approaching the table to get their order.
Senna ordered the oysters with garlic-parmesan sauce, and Alvira ordered the sauteed sea scallops with caramelized apples.
“Excellent choices,” the waiter said with a subsequent brisk spin away from the table.
“What a beautiful place, Senna.
Really this is too much just to celebrate the first tomatoes I grew in the garden, like, this is absurd,” Alvira said.
Senna laughed and said, “No, those were really the best tomatoes I’ve ever had.
We had to celebrate.”
They talked and laughed as the sun sank below the horizon, and the glow from the ocean was replaced by the glow from the chandeliers.
The waiter eventually returned with their meals, and everything was even more delicious than they had expected, especially the oysters, which Senna said tasted like the ocean.
Then he paused and looked at Alvira meaningfully.
“It’s really been the best three years of my life with you.
I couldn’t imagine it any other way, and I don’t want to.
I really want to spend the rest of my years eating garden tomatoes, whatever it is, with you.”
Alvira smiled, “I want the same with you too, Senna.”
Senna nodded at the waiter who had been watching attentively, and he quickly strode over to place a small, elegant cake topped with the ring in front of Alvira.
Her eyes widened in shock when she realized what she was looking at.
“Alvira, will you marry me?
I love you, and I will never stop loving you.”
Alvira started to cry.
The room became silent, and everyone turned to their table.
“Yes, of course, yes!” she shouted as she wiped away tears.
The neighboring tables exploded in applause.
The waiter returned with a bottle of champagne and popped it.
All of this went unnoticed by Senna and Alvira as they looked into each others’ eyes, and he slipped the ring onto her finger.
She held up her hand to admire it, and her glittering tears of joy matched the shine from her ring.
Charlie saw Alma as they walked into class and he motioned for her to come sit in the back next to him: they had business to discuss.
Charlie and Alma were both economics students with entrepreneurial bents.
They were also both very busy and in the same class.
After talking at a party, Charlie had discovered that Alma was looking for financing for her web development company.
It was serendipitous because he had been talking with other members of his venture capital group about making an investment.
His financial group had come to a decision that morning about Alma’s idea, and he didn't want to wait until after class to discuss the proposal with her.
The class was in a large auditorium with small, foldable desks on the side of each cushioned chair.
There were large windows on both sides of the hall, and they could see the first flurries of a winter storm starting outside.
“Here we are at Lecture Seven already in History of the Eternal City,” said the professor.
“We're going to talk today about the age of the first Roman emperor: Augustus.”
She went into some recap of the last lecture, and Charlie took this as an opportunity to start talking to Alma.
“Okay so I’ve been thinking about your startup idea, and I have talked about it with my fellow investors.
We’d like to invest half of what you originally suggested.
Rather than $30,000, we start with $15,000.
We would see how the company does and then invest the other half later.”
Alma, tapping her pen on her notebook, narrowed her eyes and pursed her lips.
She turned back to the lecture as she considered this.

The professor was going on: “The senate had conferred upon him the title of Augustus the sacred and revered one, the restorer of traditional values, the city’s new religious leader, the restorer of temples.
Augustus also sought to beautify Rome, make it into a new Athens, and dispel the criticisms of Rome as disorganized and ugly.”
Alma turned back to Charlie and offered her rebuttal, “I don’t know about that: it’s not going to be possible to implement our ideas effectively unless the project is fully funded.
We would have to find other investors and that would set us back in our timeline.
Our profit projections assumed we'd be starting relatively soon, not months down the line.”
They whispered back and forth during the whole class in order to work out a compromise.
Finally, the class ended, and the professor dismissed the students with a reminder that the midterm paper was due on Thursday and that they should email their papers to the TA.
Everyone, except Charlie and Alma, packed up their things and headed out of the lecture hall to get to their next class.
“Alright, so we’ll have the $30,000 wired to you by tomorrow,” Charlie said.
This wasn't ideal for Charlie, but Alma had refused to budge, and his investment group had told him they were willing to pay the full amount if necessary.
They shook hands, walked out of the now-empty lecture hall, and made plans to sign the official paperwork the next day.
It didn’t help the situation that Calvin and Jessie were running late to the airport, since Jessie had already been fuming at Calvin and preparing to end things with him.
Upon arriving, they had only 45 minutes until their international flight would depart from Jamaica for the US.
It had been a tough vacation for them.

Jessie had really had it with Calvin’s constant ramblings about the same excruciatingly boring golfing and work stories, which he insisted on repeating to her regardless of how little interest she showed.
Calvin knew that Jessie was upset, but wasn't sure what to do besides attempting to carry on as normal and tell stories that took up the silence.

The security line was luckily very short, and once the online boarding passes were scanned they were ushered quickly through the metal detector, not having to take off their shoes or remove the liquids from their bags.
“The infrastructure of this airport is really quite poor, said Calvin as they waited for their bags to emerge from the x-ray machine."
“I really could've hidden something in my shoes quite easily.”
Jessie, exasperated at his need to broadcast his every inner thought, scowled at the conveyor belt.
“What?”, he asked.
She balled up her fists and turned to face him.
“Calvin, I really don’t think I can do this anymore.
I think it’s best that once we get to the States we part ways for good.”
Calvin said nothing as he grabbed his bag and quickly walked away.
Jessie trailed behind him as they made their way quickly toward their gate, shouting at his back in hopes of getting a response.
“So now you have nothing to say?
Every time we talk, you are just looking for a way to steer the conversation back into your stories.”
Calvin didn't slow his pace, gritting his teeth and staring straight ahead.
He was very frustrated that he had been trying to appease Jessie this whole time and this was how she responded.
The silence was punctuated only by the rapid rhythmic clacking of their suitcase wheels over the tile floor as they continued power-walking through the terminal.
“Well?” Jessie said, and Calvin finally turned to her.
“Well, Jessie, this makes perfect sense.
If you feel this way, then I don’t want to keep boring you, and I agree, let’s part ways once we make it back.
You should’ve spoken up about my apparent intolerability before you decided to plan this vacation.”
He was clearly hurt, but thought it was pointless to argue.
They finally made it to the gate, just as they heard the final call for passengers boarding their flight.
They scanned their tickets, and the annoyed flight attendant shooed them onto the jet bridge and then closed the door behind them.
Luckily, they had forgotten to arrange seats next to each other on the flight back.
They both had first-class tickets, but Jessie was headed for seat 1B while Calvin's seat was 4F.
Before Jessie sat down, she took a deep breath and then awkwardly shook Calvin’s hand, mumbling, “Well, have a nice flight.”
He laughed in disbelief and walked to his window seat three rows back to get ready for takeoff.
Both were upset but glad that they would have this flight to mull things over and recenter.
Leon and  Ariana hurried into the classroom at the same time, and Leon did a double-take when he saw her.

This was his first day after transferring to this university, and he had assumed that he wouldn’t know anyone on campus, but he couldn't shake the nagging feeling  that he had seen her somewhere before.
They were both a bit late, so they quickly slid into seats next to each other in the back of the small classroom.
This room was usually used for small meetings, but had been rearranged with the table pushed to the side and chairs set up in rows to face the projector screen.
There were no windows in the room, since they were down in the sub-basement of the history department.
Leon, trying to figure out where he had seen her before, could not stop looking over at Ariana.
Ariana was oblivious to Leon’s gaze and was only focused on getting ready for class.
“Good afternoon class,” the professor began.
“Welcome to Egyptian Cultural Studies.
Today we will be talking about mummification, one of the most famous and often misunderstood customs in ancient Egyptian society.”
Leon pulled out his notebook and tried to concentrate on the class.
Within a few minutes though he found his attention wandering back to Ariana.
He decided to do something about his hunch so he ripped off a corner of a page in his notebook, wrote a note, and set it on her desk.
“Hi, sorry to distract you from mummies, but you look really familiar, it read."
It continued: “Do I know you from somewhere?”
She looked at the note with surprise, and then turned to notice Leon for the first time.
She instantly liked him when she saw him; he had very soft eyes and sharp features, a combination that made him seem  trustworthy and genuine.
He smiled at her and she flashed him a smile back.
Then she turned the note over to the back and started to write a reply.
Meanwhile the professor continued, “One may well question why the ancient Egyptians spent so much time and effort on their funerary practices.
Not only was the mummification process itself a complicated affair, but there were also elaborate rituals before, during, and after death.
The practice required teams of experts with years of training and took a total of 70 days to complete.”
Ariana passed the note back to Leon, and she had replied, “No, but maybe my twin and I were separated at birth.”
They passed notes back and forth the whole class like they were back in high school.
Near the end of the lecture, Leon wrote, “Would you like to go to dinner tonight?”
Ariana read the note, and looked at him and nodded her head
She wrote back on the slip of paper, “Pick me up at 6 in front of Patton Hall.”
Then the professor ended the lecture and announced to the class that they would have their first quiz next class on Friday on mummification.
Everyone packed up and started heading out, as well as Sophie and Leon.
They approached each other smiling, and Leon said, “Well it was great to meet you, again, or maybe not again, but regardless it was great to meet you.”
She replied, “Yes, it was.
I have to run to my next class, but I’ll see you later tonight.”
She waved as they parted ways outside of the door of the classroom, and Leon was still trying to figure out where he had seen her before as he watched her go.
Simon and Carina noticed each other as they walked into the grocery store at the same time, their carts nearly colliding as they squeezed into the entrance.
They were both new to the Boston area, and this was their first time in this store.
It kind of looked like a large warehouse, with high unfurnished ceilings, industrial lights, and large packages of food.
They went off along separate routes, but soon ended up back together in the meat section.
They were both preparing for barbecues, so they were looking over the same cuts of meat.
Simon really wanted to talk to Carina, and Carina really wanted to say something to Simon, but they felt embarrassed striking up a conversation with a stranger.
Carina suddenly turned to Simon and, pointing at a Cornish hen, asked, “Isn’t this meat cute?”
He laughed, and said, “It is very cute.
Probably the younger brother of this guy,” and he picked up a regular-sized chicken.
“Unlucky family,” she responded.
They continued to chat as they picked out their groceries.
Simon helped Carina pick out the best ribs and his personal favorite barbeque sauce, and she helped him gather the  peppers, onions, and spices for a vegetable kabob she recommended.
When they were both finished shopping, they went to the checkout area.
Simon was disappointed to see that the lines were short, since he had been hoping for an excuse to spend more time with Carina.
They had real chemistry, and both of them could definitely see a future together despite having just met.
“So you haven’t been around the city much?”, Simon asked.
“No, not really.
I’ve mainly been working and setting up my apartment.”
Simon asked her, “Ok well, if you’d like I could pick you up next weekend, and we could go around Harvard Square and get dinner.
There are a lot of great places around there, and it’s really nice during the summer.
The Harvard campus is also beautiful.”
Carina smiled, “I’d love to: that sounds great!”
She quickly entered her number in his phone, since they only had to wait a couple minutes in line.
Then it was her turn to check out with the cashier.
Simon, wanting to make a gesture of his affection, lifted up the divider on the conveyor belt and said to the cashier, “Actually these are together.
Carina, I’ve got it.
This was kind-of a date today.”
Carina blushed and laughed; she thought this was ridiculous but also very sweet.
The cashier rolled her eyes when they weren’t looking, and she scanned the rest of his items.
The total came to $120, and he paid with his credit card.
Carina thanked him, and they took the groceries and walked out.
As they were walking towards the exit, Carina reluctantly said goodbye since she was running late for the barbeque she was hosting that afternoon.
They hugged and parted ways, stealing glances at each other as they both walked back to their cars.
Thomas, dreading the conversation he was about to have, got to Annika’s Finer Diner early.
The restaurant had a kitschy charm and was reminiscent of a diner from the 70’s.
A bell chimed as the door swung open and Sadie entered to find Thomas deep in thought on a bench by the door.
He jumped up and gave her a side hug.
“How was your day?”, he asked.
She clung onto him, “It was okay.
I missed you today.”
He looked at the hostess coming towards them.
“Can we have a table in the back?”, Thomas asked.
She shrugged and, as she loudly popped her bubblegum, replied, “Sure, honey, this way.”
She led them to the back of the restaurant where there were dimly lit tables.
“Is this alright?”, the hostess asked.
Thomas cleared his throat and tried not to grimace at the stained fabric that lined the booth.
“This is great.
Thank you,” Thomas said.
Sadie slipped into the cushioned seat and grabbed Thomas’ hand.
“Tell me about your day!”, Sadie sang as Thomas sat down.
He looked at her silently and pulled his hand slowly from hers.
Sadie gave him a puzzled look.
Thomas looked away and took a deep breath.
Sadie asked, “What’s wrong?”
Thomas picked at his fingernails.
“Sadie, I’ve been thinking, and I need to figure out some stuff… on my own.”
Sadie’s mouth popped open for a moment.
Then she swallowed and shifted back in her seat.
“Things have been really picking up at work.
And I’m not sure that this is the job I want to do anymore.
It’s been really overwhelming between working and figuring out if I should change careers.”
The waiter appeared and interrupted the speech Thomas had been practicing.
“Hello you two!”, the waiter said.
“Have you decided what you would like?”
Thomas and Sadie realized there were menus on the table, and they glanced at the lengthy list quickly.
There were so many strange dishes they had never heard of before, so they settled on familiar orders.
“I’ll have a burger, no tomatoes,” Thomas said.
Sadie asked about the reuben, and the waiter told her it was excellent.
Once she agreed to get that, he walked away.
Sadie and Thomas looked at each other.
“So what are you saying?”, Sadie asked.
Thomas replied, “I want to take a break for awhile.
You know, have space to figure out what I’m supposed to be doing.”
Sadie quietly burst into tears.
Nevertheless, people sitting at the adjacent table looked over and quickly averted their gaze as they realized what was happening.
“Is this really what you want?
I don’t understand.
I don’t understand.
Things were fine.
We don’t have to hang out all the time, or as much as we do now.”
Thomas chewed on his bottom lip and picked at his now bleeding hangnail.
At that moment, the waiter arrived with the burger and reuben and set them on the table.
“Is there anything else I can get for you two?
Will you be getting dessert tonight?”, he asked.
“Oh no, we’re good, thanks,” Thomas said.
Once the waiter had walked away still oblivious to the situation, Thomas sighed and said, “Sadie, I’m sorry.
You are so great, and I love hanging out with you.
But I need some time.
I’m so sorry.”
He grabbed her hand, and she pulled it out of his.
“Sadie,” he said.
She stood up, grabbed half of the reuben and shook it at him as she growled, “Don’t follow me, and don’t talk to me anymore!”
Sadie's heels clacked loudly against the black and white linoleum, and the bell above the door jingled cheerfully as the door closed behind her.
Thomas sat there for awhile in shock at how quickly everything transpired.
He grabbed his burger and took a bite of it, creating a dry and fishy taste in his mouth.
He dropped it back on his plate and wondered if the restaurant was responsible for the foul taste.
Ms. Bianchi and Ms. Morrison walked into the grocery store at the same time, and, after a moment of mutual recognition, greeted each other and shook hands.
“Thank you again for inviting me here to discuss my business proposal,” said Ms. Bianchi, “And it’s a pleasure to be out of the office.”
As a salesperson for an Italian cheese company that was trying to expand its outreach to more mainstream grocery stores, this meeting could be a big break for her.
Her sales target, Ms. Morrison,  who had a reputation for being a bit quirky, was a corporate buyer for a large chain grocery store.

She was known for doing things unconventionally: for example, she said that she liked to make deals with suppliers in the place where the products were sold- “to keep their minds focused on what’s important.”
They chatted a little in the front of the grocery store, which was surrounded by pumpkins and halloween decorations set up in special displays for the holiday season.
Ms. Bianchi and Ms. Morrison walked to the cheese section, and Ms. Morrison picked up a block of parmesan.
“We have quite a selection here.
I don’t know that it needs an additional section for more gourmet cheeses.”
Ms. Bianchi's confidence faltered for a minute at this remark, but then she launched into her prepared pitch.
“Ms. Morrison, I think you would agree that selling food is more than just providing variety, but also about providing the highest quality.
You don’t have cheeses made in America that are like ours, it is true.
Your store could be providing American consumers with a dimension in taste that they've never known before with our product.

I propose that you give it a shot, buy $1000 worth of cheese products for a few stores, and see how the sales increase not only in our cheeses but also in products related to cheeses: crackers, jams, olives.
The availability of a finer product leads to the appreciation of the product, and your consumers will start to consume in a new, more profitable way.”
Ms. Bianchi picked up a box of crackers by the cheese section, and said, “Here, I will buy these, and we can try some of our cheeses that I've brought with me.”
Ms. Morrison, who was thinking, nodded in agreement and said, “That sounds like a great idea.
Let’s head to check out, and those crackers are on me.”
They walked over to the checkout area.
There was a very long line, and it was very busy in the checkout area as people were stocking up for Halloween parties and trick-or-treating.

Since they had almost a 10 minute wait in line, Ms. Bianchi handed a sheet with printed graphs to Ms. Morrison the increase in profits that several other stores had seen after starting to carry their products.
Eventually, Ms. Morrison replied, “You know what, I think you've convinced me that this could work.
We've been trying to find a way to add a little European cachet to our stores.
There's still a problem though - I'm worried we'll be paying out the nose for the import taxes.
Is that the case?"
It was Ms. Morrison’s turn to checkout, and the two businesswomen continued to talk back and forth as she did so.
The cashier scanned the crackers, and Ms. Bianchi watched in amusement as Ms. Morrison paid the $6 price entirely in quarters from a wallet bulging with change.
They shortly came to an agreement and would have enough cheese shipments, $5000 worth, to different stores to qualify for a subsidized import tax.
Ms. Bianchi retrieved some of her samples from her car, and they toasted their new deal with crackers topped with fresh mozzarella.
Sven and Isabel walked hurriedly from the cab into the Barcelona Airport after an incredible weekend with Isabel’s family, which had wiped away any doubts Sven had had about his decision to propose.
They were a little pressed for time, with only a little over an hour until their flight would take off to go back to the US, but they already had their online boarding passes and no checked luggage.
When Isabel stopped to rummage through her purse looking for her phone, Sven turned his back to her and took the velvet box out of his backpack, opening it to look at the ring he bought her.
He had received her parents’ blessing during the trip, and he was almost giddy with excitement.
He tilted the ring backward and forward, despite having already studied it daily since he had purchased it a few weeks ago.
It was a simple design, with a clear, white diamond on a thin silver band.
“Sven, let’s go! ” Isabel said.
Sven discretely closed the box and put it in his pocket.
They entered the security line, weaving through the roped walkways to the front.
When they were up, Isabel realized her laptop was buried somewhere in her duffle bag.
Sven had to hold the growing mound of objects she pulled from her bag until she unearthed the laptop.
She set it into a bin and then had to unstrap her leather boots and put everything else into the bins.
Finally, she relieved Sven of his holding duties, and he hurriedly deposited his own backpack on the belt as the people behind them glared without shame.
Sven went into the millimeter wave scanner after Isabel, put his hands up, and the metal bars whirled around him.
“Sir, please step to the side.
You need to empty your pockets,” the security guard said.
With a sinking feeling Sven realized the mistake he had made forgetting to put the ring back in his bag, as Isabel and the guard both looked at him expectantly.
Sven,  deciding he would make the best of the situation, grabbed Isabel's hand as he reached into his pocket.
He got down on one knee and, giggling slightly at her confused look, said, “Isabel, this isn't quite how I'd planned this, but - will you marry me?”
The security guard gasped.
All the people who were putting their shoes back on and gathering their belongings stopped what they were doing and walked closer to the couple.
Isabel was astonished, and far too shy to respond in front of the backup of passengers waiting behind them.
She attempted to stammer a response as she frantically grabbed her and Sven’s shoes, leaving Sven to retrieve their bags.
Both of them slipping in their socked feet, she fled onto the concourse with Sven trying to catch up behind her.
Everyone in the terminal was looking at them with confusion as Sven, holding the bags in one hand and the open ring box in the other, finally caught up to her.
“Isabel?”
He watched her face as she turned, trying to read her expression.
Her eyes were wide, but she was smiling as she hyperventilated, “Of course yes, Sven, yes!”
They dropped their belongings and hugged, and Sven slipped the ring onto Isabel’s finger.
After getting their shoes back on, they practically skipped to the gate, filled with joy.
Sven high-fived a confused shoe-shine attendant as they passed.
They sat down outside their gate, having actually made good time, until the attendant called for passengers.
They boarded, sitting together in first class, and had a glass of champagne to celebrate the departure into their new life together.

Some of their neighboring passengers who had witnessed the proposal congratulated them, and a woman next to them showed them that she had been live-tweeting the whole event and that it was already going viral online.
Isabel slid down in her seat with her hands over her face, both embarrassed and overjoyed at the same time.

instructText: The next task in the experiment is to recall each story to the best of your ability.
You will be presented with the story title, names, the images, and a blank text box for each story.
Describe the story with as many details as you can remember in the space provided.
When you are finished recalling one story, to move onto the next one hit ‘return’.
There is a 5 minute time limit to make your response.

recall: Senna is planning on proposing to alvira. they are at a restaurant and senna goes to use the bathroom at one point. they are joking about the tomatoes that alvira is growing at her home, and senna uses this in his proposal as he says that he wants to share those tomatoes with her for the rest of their lives. this event takes place at night and the restaurant had a nice view of the ocean from its windows.

Charlie and alma meet each other in a class for the first time. charlie thinks that he recognizes alma from somewhere, and he gets her attention by passing her a note. they are in a class and the professor informs them that they have an exam on friday.

Calvin and jessie are boarding a plane back home to the u.s. jessie is not happy with calvin and is planning on breaking up with him. as they go through security, calvin is trying to distract from jessie's upsetness, but jessie displays her frustrations with calvin. jessie eventually states that she thinks that they should split up when they return to the states. they are late arriving to the airport, but are fortunate that they do not have to remove all of their items from their bags when going through security. they also are both sitting in first class, but they do not have seats next to each other so they have time to self-reflect by themselves. jessie tells calvin that she hopes he has a nice flight.

Leon and ariana are both in class. leon is new to the school and does not think he will know anyone there. when he sees ariana, however, he feels like he recognizes her. leon sends her a note and ariana looks over at leon and is attracted to him. meanwhile, the professor is lecturing and announces at the end of class that there is an exam coming up on friday. they agree to go on a date in the future.

Simon and carina meet each other at a grocery store in boston. carina is new to the area and this is her first time at the store. they are both shopping for barbecue food and simon makes a joke using the chicken in the barbecue section. when they get to the front of the store, simon is disappointed that the lines are short because he wants to spend more time with carina. he removes the separator for their items at the checkout line and tells carina that this was essentially a date and that he would treat her. he asks if she would like to meet up with him at some point, and he suggests going to the harvard lawn as he says it is beautiful. she agrees to this proposal.

Thomas and sadie meet up at a diner and thomas is preparing to break up with sadie. sadie, however, is very excited to see thomas and states that she missed him during the day. they are seated at a booth, and when sadie asks thomas how his day was and holds his hand, thomas moves his hand away and starts telling her how he is feeling. he says that he thinks he needs some time alone and some time to think. while he is talking and sadie expresses her shock, their waiter comes over and takes their order. they both have to rush to pick something, and the menu is filled with many unfamiliar items. thomas decides on a burger with tomatoes. sadie asks if they can just spend less time together instead of splitting up. eventually, they are brought their food by the oblivious waiter and thomas asks sadie if they can be friends. sadie, however, does not want to talk to him again and leaves. thomas takes a bite of his burger and is not fond of the taste. he questions if this was done intentionally by the restaurant as it is noted that many of the customers picked up on what was happening as a result of sadie's reaction.

Ms. morrison is attempting to convince ms. bianchi to add morrison's cheese products to bianchi's store. they discuss this deal in the store because that is where morrison likes to conduct her business so that they can keep their focus on the sale. when they go to the cheese section, bianchi states that they already have a large assortment of cheese and they do not need to add more. morrison, however, says that one can always improve upon the quality of the food. they discuss this more as they wait in line to check out. the line is rather long, and they end up waiting for ten minutes. in this time, morrison is able to convince bianchi to buy her products. after they check out, morrison grabs some samples from her car and they feast on mozzarella and crackers.

Sven is planning on proposing to isabel and has his ring in his pocket. they are at an airport and preparing to go through security. isabel has sven hold some items as she goes through her bag and searches for her laptop. when they go through security, sven is asked by a security guard to remove everything from his pockets. he realizes that he left the ring in his pocket and decides to take advantage of the situation and proposes to isabel in the security line. she is shocked and does not seem to want to answer while being rushed by everyone trying to get through security. she grabs her items and rushes to the concourse and sven follows closely behind. when he asks her again, she says yes. they find out many people were recording the proposal and some even posted it on social media. isabel did not seem too fond of the added attention.
